<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-01T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-01T22:00:00-05:00" n="1020" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1020">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5294/579: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-02T12:00:00+09:00">March 2,
                                1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 2—2:17 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>42. Department’s 28, February 28, 6 p.m. Instructions in paragraph 2 were
                            carried out this morning. The Minister said that he fully understood the
                            considerations set forth and had had them in mind in answering questions
                            both in the Diet and from the press. He assured me that he would
                            continue to avoid giving specifications.</p>
                        <p>I did not touch on the point of constitutionality.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>